Here is our implementation of it. To be perfectly honest, I don’t like how I created it, but it was more of a last minute addition (but it works).

In my command that I use to rev the shooter if a note is in the robot, I have it call a function that rumbles the controller in RobotContainer and has it stop rumbling if a note is not in the robot.

// Called when the command is initially scheduled.

@Override

public void initialize() {}

// Called every time the scheduler runs while the command is scheduled.

@Override

public void execute() {

//If there is a note loaded and our rev speed is greater than the input speed, run at rev speed

if(ShooterSub.getFeedBeltSwitch() && (this.shooterSpeed.getAsDouble() < ShooterConstants.kRevSpeed)){

ShooterSub.setShooter(ShooterConstants.kRevSpeed);

RobotContainer.setRightRumbleDriver(0.25);

LEDSub.blinkSolidColor(0, 255, 0);

}else{

ShooterSub.setShooter(this.shooterSpeed.getAsDouble());

RobotContainer.setRightRumbleDriver(0.0);

if(SwerveSub.isAllianceBlue()){

LEDSub.setColorChase(120, 60, SwerveSub.getVelocity()*5);

}else{

LEDSub.setColorChase(60, 120, SwerveSub.getVelocity()*5);

}

This is the function I use to set the rumble. I’m not really sure if having this as a static method and the controllers as static objects (so I can rumble them) is the best way to do this, but I’m not sure on any other way to do this.

s_SwerveSubsystem.setDefaultCommand(driveFieldOrientedAnglularVelocity);

}

